	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Senecaville O.</placeName> <date>June 20. 1867</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">As I have the impression that<lb/> you never read the &#8220;Israelite&#8221; I take the liberty<lb/> to send you the <sic>inclosed</sic> article cut from the<lb/> Israelite.  I thought it would be interesting to<lb/> you to learn that thoughts so favorable to the<lb/> reality of miracles appear in that paper.  I take<lb/> it for granted that this article is much more<lb/> agreeable to your views than the treatment which<lb/> the same subject and the manna receive in<lb/> <persName>Dr. Wise&#39;s</persName> History.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In contending&#44; however&#44; for the historical<lb/> truth of miracles.  I am afraid that among<lb/> your people we have now a mighty current<lb/> against us.  When I was in <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName> more<lb/> than a year ago&#44; examining the <persName>Licking Co.</persName> relics&#44;<lb/> I met a <persName>Mr. Moering</persName>&#44; an aged Israelite&#44; who told<lb/> me that he believed that the whole Jewish commu&#61;<lb/>nity were sliding into the views of <persName>Drs Lilienthal</persName><lb/> and <persName>Wise</persName> on miracles&#44; and that these men<lb/> would succeed in what they had undertaken<lb/> so that in twenty years orthodox Judaism would<lb/> be lost.  And what appeared to me stranger<lb/> he himself appeared to look on it as all right.<lb/>  He intimated that there might have been some con&#61;<lb/>cealed knowledge and use of gunpowder by <persName>Moses</persName><lb/> in the destruction of the company of <persName>Korah</persName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The common way of speaking of such things<lb/> among Gentiles is just this&#44; that the Jews are now<lb/> going right into infidelity&#44; and that they are proving<lb/> unfaithful to their great trust in the preservation<lb/> of the truth.</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>Do not understand me however<lb/> as writing these things to discourage you.<lb/>  It is one comfort that though error may<lb/> triumph for an age or century&#44; time will<lb/> eventually give <hi rend="underline">truth</hi> the unfading victory.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Excuse me for this interruption<lb/> of your studies by a few friendly words&#44;<lb/> and believe me</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Yours most respectfully&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">M. R. Miller</persName>.</p>
		</body>
